        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer64305166" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18373179631866701965">It&apos;s hard to believe that Alexander McCall-Smith, the same author who wrote the Number 1 Ladies Detective Agency and the 44 Scotland Street series, wrote this book from the Sunday Philosophy Club series. So far, I think that this is the worst of the four-book series. The main character, Isabel Dalhousie, a philosopher and professor of ethics, can&apos;t seem to get through an hour of her day without analyzing everything into the ground. She spends so much time worrying about her feelings, beliefs, an</span>
  <span id="freeText18373179631866701965" style="display:none">It's hard to believe that Alexander McCall-Smith, the same author who wrote the Number 1 Ladies Detective Agency and the 44 Scotland Street series, wrote this book from the Sunday Philosophy Club series. So far, I think that this is the worst of the four-book series. The main character, Isabel Dalhousie, a philosopher and professor of ethics, can't seem to get through an hour of her day without analyzing everything into the ground. She spends so much time worrying about her feelings, beliefs, and actions (as well as those of others) that the stories just stagnate. What probably started out as a clever idea to get the reader to think of the moral and ethical implication of everyday interactions has become, unfortunately, a very boring book. It just plodded along and I could hardly wait to finish. A big disappointment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18373179631866701965" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
