<div id="review_220334012" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/220334012" />
    <a title="Jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2873372-jo"><img alt="Jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1269011265p2/2873372.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/220334012?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jo" href="/user/show/2873372-jo">Jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780375423000" href="/book/show/15902.The_Right_Attitude_to_Rain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2873372-jo?shelf=cozy">cozy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer220334012" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8957414632447780775">An enjoyable book three with a slightly different feel. Not a mystery, more of a transformational book with pivotal character &amp; plot development. Whereas in book 1 I found it hard to buy into Isabel being in her early forties, over the course of book 2 &amp; 3 we see Isabel less stogy &amp; nosy and more open, active, freer, helping the reader buy into her being a fab 40. I liked the character of Florence, an older wiser woman who encourages Isabel to live without regrets. I equally enjoyed Mimi too, ni</span>
  <span id="freeText8957414632447780775" style="display:none">An enjoyable book three with a slightly different feel. Not a mystery, more of a transformational book with pivotal character &amp; plot development. Whereas in book 1 I found it hard to buy into Isabel being in her early forties, over the course of book 2 &amp; 3 we see Isabel less stogy &amp; nosy and more open, active, freer, helping the reader buy into her being a fab 40. I liked the character of Florence, an older wiser woman who encourages Isabel to live without regrets. I equally enjoyed Mimi too, nice to see Isabel enjoying her kin and welcoming with ease these quirky people into her home. The romance with Jamie is fragile and Isabel's angst around it is so sweet and sad at the same time.<br /><br />As to the plot, the visit from her cousin is a nice addition and it sheds light on Isabel's American mother. And, despite the above teaser description, Mimi's husband is Joe. Rich Texan Tom is a friend of Joe &amp; Mimi and Tom doesn't come off as a creeper at all. Nor does Isabel question Mimi's marriage. Actually that promo description completely misses the developments of this edition to the series. Must have been written by someone who didn't read the book.<br /><br />Looking forward to book 4.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8957414632447780775" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


